More than 50 people were killed and over 500 others were injured when the train swung off the tracks. JOHANNESBURG The International Relations and Cooperation Department (Dirco) has sent its condolences to the government and people of Cameroon, in the wake of deadly train crash thats left the country reeling. More than 50 people were killed and over 500 others were injured when the packed passenger train travelling from the capital Yaounde swung off the tracks late yesterday. Officials have confirmed that children are among the dead and government is now investigating claims that the locomotive was heavily overloaded at the time of the crash. International relations spokesperson Clayson Monyela said, We dont have any information suggesting that any South African is affected by this train accident and we wish those who are injured a speedy recovery.